Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Definition of the auxiliary arrays", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.888315173503672*^9, 3.888315249112604*^9}, {
  3.8883153026090937`*^9, 3.8883153149727306`*^9}, {3.888315800792353*^9, 
  3.888315802330164*^9}, {3.9077382535011215`*^9, 3.907738255398263*^9}, {
  3.9079184731747074`*^9, 
  3.9079185042453585`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"46c87ec6-f6e4-4f7e-bcc5-\
a5d69b95c097"],

Cell["\<\
Arrays specifying the Nambu indices (cf. NambuBogAntidiag), the operator type \
(cf. SQTypeBogAntidiag) and distinguishing internal from external \
single-particle indices (cf. IntExtBogAntidiag) are defined, in accordance \
with the conventions for the second-quantization operators in the header of \
the notebook. In particular, to external (internal) single-particle indices \
the value of \[OpenCurlyQuote]1\[CloseCurlyQuote] (\[OpenCurlyQuote]0\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]) is assigned, whereas for second-quantization operators of \
creation (annihilation) type the associated array entry is \[OpenCurlyQuote]0\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] (\[OpenCurlyQuote]1\[CloseCurlyQuote]). For Nambu indices, \
the convention is straightforward.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9077382215659647`*^9, {3.9077382923703613`*^9, 3.9077384065565405`*^9}, {
   3.9077384522680173`*^9, 3.9077384848449383`*^9}, {3.9077430709590244`*^9, 
   3.907743126073769*^9}, {3.9077450424291105`*^9, 3.9077450765315623`*^9}, {
   3.907918517166184*^9, 3.9079188444385033`*^9}, 3.9091515935484114`*^9, {
   3.9092041717880774`*^9, 3.9092041805155473`*^9}, {3.909825793352968*^9, 
   3.909825806952718*^9}, {3.9098365799193134`*^9, 3.909836589037108*^9}, {
   3.9100849354462347`*^9, 3.910084945154549*^9}, {3.9100985340207205`*^9, 
   3.91009854700209*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1dcb8ab6-3c1f-4faf-b772-\
139ad120d1dd"],

